{"text":"<p>The V and A brings together more than two hundred garments, accessories, paintings and archival items that trace Elsa Schiaparelli's creative alliances from the 1920s to the present. The layout moves between salon style displays and intimate cases of sketches and letters, so the Tears evening dress from 1938, made in collaboration with Salvador Dalí, reads differently beside a Jean Cocteau sketch than it does near a later Daniel Roseberry gown. The Tears dress acts as a clear highlight because it connects couture technique to a theatrical surrealist gesture and to the fabric designs that Dalí supplied for the house. ([vam.ac.uk](https://www.vam.ac.uk/exhibitions/schiaparelli))</p>

<p>There are two don’t miss elements on the route. The first is the Skeleton dress, an item already in the V and A collection that emphasises how Schiaparelli translated imagery into structural dress. The second is an ankle length black silk jersey coat from 1937 made with Jean Cocteau and Lesage, which shows artisan embroidery and applied motifs at close range. Contemporary interventions punctuate earlier work: a Matador long sheath gown by Daniel Roseberry and a gilded brass lung necklace appear as deliberate modern echoes. Paintings and photographs by Pablo Picasso and Man Ray sit with costume drawings, so the dialogues between artist and couturier are tangible rather than abstract. ([vam.ac.uk](https://www.vam.ac.uk/exhibitions/schiaparelli))</p>

<p>A small hidden gem is the display of factory notes and Lesage embroidery samples that survives in one of the cabinets; these concentrate technical information that often goes unseen in glamour led narratives and reveal stitch by stitch how motifs were built. The curatorial text points to cross channel trade in materials and to Schiaparelli's early business papers when attention turns to loans and provenance. The Sainsbury Gallery holds much of the run and timed entry applies for the major galleries while the museum keeps standard opening times on its main site. There are members previews and morning view sessions around opening dates which reflect the scale of the loans and conservation work involved. The presentation aims to let garments, sketches and small works read together across decades without flattening differences between original works and later reinterpretations. ([vam.ac.uk](https://www.vam.ac.uk/exhibitions/schiaparelli))"}
